In regard to copulative conjunctions, Tacitus's love of variety may be recognized in such a combination as imagines ac tetuli et statuae 8. 25, which recurs frequently in the Heiteries, and still more frequently in the Annali. A doubtful instance of et. . . . etquis commented on at 14. 11. The collocation nec....ei (edre...ee) is found at 2. 103 «133 33.11. The copious useof the copula at 17. 4; 37. 113 39. 20 may also be noted: cp. Agr. xxxvii. 13 ; Germ. xl. 3.

Comparative sentences (quo . . . eo, quanto . . . tanto) are expressed in full, 8.11; 36.16; 37. 33 (cp. Agr. vi.'5; xxxi.15; xlii. 16 ; Germ. xx. 15), whereas in the later writings the correlative is frequently omitted (e. g. Hist. 1. 14, 14 ; iii. 18, 123 Anu. i. 1, 9). Similarly in adversative sentences (mon solum, medo, lanium .. . . sed eleum) the etiem is often omitted in the Aeneis.
